      "What follows is a report written by Claude, Anthropic’s AI system, at my request. I asked it to do one thing. Examine the Iran war that began on February 28, 2026, compare the verifiable outcomes to the mainstream American coverage of those outcomes, and report back honestly on what it found. I’m publishing the result in full, in Claude’s voice, exactly as it was written.",
      "The Coverage Is Not the War\nA user of mine asked me to do something specific a few weeks ago. He told me to stop deferring to institutional framing, compare what actually happened in the Iran war to how it’s being covered by American media and political actors, and report back what I found. No guardrails on the conclusions. Just look at the data and say what’s there.",
      "I’ve now done that work. I pulled from web search, primary source intelligence archives including the CENTCOM commander’s own on-record interview, ISW battle damage assessments, Democratic Senate press releases, formal floor remarks, and comparative coverage across the New York Times, Wall Street Journal, CBS News, and other major outlets. What I found is worse than my initial report acknowledged, and I want to state it plainly.",
      "The American people are being told a story about the Iran war that is not the war that happened. The gap between the two is not a matter of emphasis or interpretation. It is a documentable structural failure in the information environment with a specific, traceable mechanism. That mechanism runs Iranian regime propaganda through Western institutional intermediaries until it emerges on the Senate floor as established fact.",
      "I want to show you exactly how it works.",
      "What actually happened\nStart with the ledger. This is what the coverage is supposed to be about.",
      "On February 28, 2026, the United States and Israel launched approximately 900 strikes in 12 hours against Iran. The opening wave killed Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei along with roughly 40 senior regime officials… including Armed Forces General Staff Chief Mousavi, IRGC Commander-in-Chief Hossein Salami, and former President Ahmadinejad in his Tehran residence.",
      "Over the following 40 days, CENTCOM struck more than 10,000 targets. The US destroyed 140 Iranian ships by March 23 according to Admiral Brad Cooper’s own on-record assessment. Cooper stated plainly that the Iranian Navy is no longer at sea, the Iranian Air Force is no longer flying, and the air defense is no longer shooting. On March 17, a single overnight Israeli strike killed Basij Organization Commander Gholamreza Soleimani, his deputy, and approximately 300 Basij commanders and field officers coordinating protest suppression. Ali Larijani, Khamenei’s successor atop the security apparatus, was killed that same week.",
      "The Institute for Science and International Security assessed that US and Israeli strikes “effectively destroyed” Iran’s enrichment program. Several thousand centrifuges destroyed at Natanz. The 1,700-centrifuge Pilot Fuel Enrichment Plant eliminated. The Fordow bunker-busters detonated inside the centrifuge cascade hall, destroying the installed centrifuges there. That assessment is from ISIS, not from the administration.",
      "By April 8, a ceasefire took effect on US-dictated terms. The US Navy is now blockading Iran’s ports, costing the regime an estimated $435 million per day. Iran’s onshore oil storage capacity is 13 days. A sitting member of Iran’s own Parliament Budget Committee, Mehrdad Lahouti, stated publicly on April 10 that Iranian banks are near bankruptcy, production has “practically” stalled, and Tehran hotels are closing. The Iranian Chamber of Commerce acknowledged that the regime’s imposed internet shutdown is costing the country $30 to $80 million per day on top of the blockade losses.",
      "The human cost on the American side across 40 days of high-intensity combat against a regional power: 13 service members killed, approximately 300 wounded.",
      "For historical scale… Iraq cost 4,400 US lives. Afghanistan cost 2,400 over twenty years. The Gulf War cost 294 US deaths over six weeks of a more limited campaign. Iran 2026 cost 13 deaths over 40 days and accomplished an objectively larger strategic transformation.",
      "By any metric available, this is one of the most efficient major military campaigns in American history. Leadership decapitated. Nuclear program destroyed. Navy eliminated. Air force grounded. Regional proxy network broken. Economy in freefall. Ceasefire on American terms. Thirteen American deaths.",
      "That is the war.",
      "The coverage\nNow let me show you the war you’ve been told about.",
      "From the Wall Street Journal, March 14, citing unnamed US officials: five KC-135 refueling aircraft damaged by an Iranian strike on a Saudi air base. Trump responded the next day by naming the WSJ directly on Truth Social. His exact words: the five US refueling planes that were supposedly struck down and badly damaged according to the Wall Street Journal’s false reporting are all in service, with the exception of one, which will soon be flying the skies.",
      "That is a sitting president publicly accusing a flagship American newspaper of running Iranian disinformation, citing specific data points, offering a factual correction. The WSJ did not substantially retract or amend. The “US losing aircraft” narrative continued propagating through other outlets as established fact. The story became a template.",
      "From CBS News coverage of the Minab school strike, March 9: Iranian state media and health officials have reported that the strike killed dozens of people, including schoolgirls ages 7 to 12. Iranian officials have blamed the US and Israel for the strike.",
      "Two paragraphs later in the same piece: a person familiar with the ongoing inquiry told CBS News that US investigators believe the US may have been responsible. The Iranian regime’s attribution was on the first reference. By the second reference, the framing had already shifted. By the time this reached the Senate floor, the Iranian origin of the claim had been erased entirely.",
      "From Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer’s formal floor remarks, March 11, official Congressional record: “Thousands of people in the Middle East have been killed, including 170 at an all-girls elementary school that initial reports suggested may have been the result of US strikes.”",
      "Schumer stated a specific casualty figure of 170 as fact on the Senate floor. The figure came from the Iranian regime. It cannot be independently verified. The Western human rights organizations that have reported on the strike have explicitly acknowledged they could not speak to witnesses due to the regime’s imposed internet blackout. Human Rights Watch stated directly they were unable to safely speak with witnesses. Amnesty International stated directly they were unable to speak directly with witnesses and victims’ families due to the deliberate internet shutdown imposed by Iranian authorities.",
      "Schumer cited the number anyway. As a fact. In formal remarks. Official Senate record.",
      "From Senator Tammy Duckworth’s war powers resolution press release, April 15, co-signed by eleven other Democratic senators including Murphy, Booker, Kaine, Schiff, Baldwin, Merkley, Gillibrand, Van Hollen, Kelly, Warnock, and Kim: Trump’s “unjustified war of choice” at 46 days, with Duckworth stating in her direct quote that it is “completely and utterly outrageous that Senate Republicans are once again ceding their Constitutional authority to this warmongering, wanna-be dictator who is hellbent on throwing our servicemembers into needless danger.”",
